<br />

<h2 class="pen"><a rel="bookmark" https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=956" title="Permanent link to this article">Games for Change</a></h2>

<div class="post">

<div class="entrytext">

	<p>OK, so watching Kerry&#8217;s lead slowly disappear causes one to growl and fret. So Bush has managed to avoid talking about the issues for a couple weeks which, again, causes one to growl and fret. So what?</p>

	<p>Thinking about it for a couple of days though, I get the feeling that after the convention Bush will peak out at about 50% support and watch it dwindle away.</p>

	<p>Bush has to deal with failures across the board and new ones that keep popping up left and right. He won&#8217;t be able to control the tempo of the debate. His supporters will go &#8220;nucular&#8221; with attacks against Kerry and while that will keep some of the electorate undecided, it won&#8217;t improve Bush&#8217;s standings. Recent polls are proving that.</p>

	<p>The key I think is whether Bush can actually run on his record and offer something to a country that has said it distinctly wants change.</p>

	<p>None of this is original thinking. Read <a href="http://www.dailykos.com">Daily Kos</a> and you&#8217;ll come to the same conclusions.</p>

	<p>I think fretting is the result of being blue in a red state, you get the feeling living here there isn&#8217;t much you can do about it all. However, I think stealing an idea from MoveOn will help.  A couple in Massachusettes held a &#8220;Games for Change&#8221; night as a fundraiser.</p>

	<p>We can get a bunch of folks who want some change in the country together here in America&#8217;s most beautiful rivertown and play games to raise money. Everyone can play games and bid on how they&#8217;ll go (the bids don&#8217;t have to be even) and all winnings go into a central pot. Playing volleyball. &#8220;We&#8217;ll bet $2 that we&#8217;ll make the next point.&#8221; Win or lose the money goes into the kitty. Start with sports and finish with cards.</p>

	<p>Maybe we can decide on a destination for the money up front, maybe we&#8217;ll hold a vote halfway through the evening as to where the money will go. The DNC? MoveOn? ACT? Congressional candidates? a percentage to each?</p>

	<p>The bottom line is we&#8217;ll have a blast, figure out who we can comiserate with and we&#8217;ll raise some change for change.</p>



 

<p class="postmetadata alt">

